The great quarry for the student is the proper names of persons aud places, whether preserved in ancient authors or in inscrip- tions, even the hrands on pottery are hunted up with eagerness that something may be gleaned from them. But as Rome imposed her laws and institutions upon the barbarians, so also did she mould their names into confonnity with her own tongue. The result in the case of the Gauls is to give us a stateliness of nomenclature surpassing that of the Romans themselves. Vercingetorix, Vercassivellaunus, Andecumborius‚ and ether polysyllabic heroes might perhaps present a more homely appearance if we had them strictly in their native dress. This latinization of Gallie names seems in one case to have led the philologists astray. Thus it has been argued from the occur· rence of forms lile Biturigas that the Gallie accusative of stem rag· was rigas. But it was the fashion among Roman writers —a lashion dictated by obvious convenience-to avail themselves of the Greek accusative itt -os in the case of proper names of the third declension. From Greelr names this fashion spread to foreign names generally, and is quite sufficient to account for the forms on which the theory of the Gallie accusative is based.
